1
00:00:00,284 --> 00:00:07,871
Asambuddhasa, homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:10,032 --> 00:00:13,637
So we're looking at this idea of hope.

3
00:00:16,039 --> 00:00:22,745
At the top of my page, I've got faith, hope, aspiration, expectation, disappointment.

4
00:00:23,486 --> 00:00:28,030
So the idea is to define all this and to see what the Buddha is actually saying.

5
00:00:29,225 --> 00:00:52,430
so faith of course uh often translated as uh confidence trust it's a foundational virtue yeah so it's one of the five spiritual faculties faith effort mindfulness concentration insight wisdom and for our purposes there are two pretty obvious enemies one is to turn it into a belief system

6
00:00:52,680 --> 00:00:55,704
which would then stop you from investigating.

7
00:00:56,084 --> 00:00:59,728
So it's the process of investigation, which is the process of liberation.

8
00:01:01,189 --> 00:01:07,536
And the subtle one about now I'm going to use the word hope because that's how it's defined in the scriptures.

9
00:01:09,518 --> 00:01:10,819
That is skeptical doubt.

10
00:01:10,838 --> 00:01:12,641
We'll come to that a little later.

11
00:01:14,141 --> 00:01:19,987
So we've got to make clear what we mean by faith, and then we can understand a bit more the other stuff.

12
00:01:20,795 --> 00:01:29,347
So remember that all our problems root back into this idea of a self, which doesn't like to, it likes to know what's going to happen.

13
00:01:30,069 --> 00:01:32,652
It's forever planning, organizing the future.

14
00:01:33,593 --> 00:01:45,070
And once we come across the Buddha Dharma, we hear about this goal, Nibbana, for some of us anyway, we don't have an idea of what Nibbana is, and yet there's some sort of hazy concept.

15
00:01:46,753 --> 00:01:49,957
And we're told it's the end of suffering, the end of compulsive desiring.

16
00:01:50,512 --> 00:01:53,216
That doesn't tell us what the actual experience is.

17
00:01:53,858 --> 00:02:08,907
And even when the Buddha's explicit, so-called explicit anyway, talks about a consciousness without boundary, without an object full of light, we still have to exercise our imagination as to sort of come up with something.

18
00:02:09,479 --> 00:02:14,104
And then we sort of have an idea that this is what Nibbana is.

19
00:02:14,604 --> 00:02:16,026
So we strive.

20
00:02:16,086 --> 00:02:36,229
The yogi sits full throttle, see, noting diligently the three characteristics of existence, how we create suffering through a wrong desire, impermanence, not self, but subconsciously somewhere trying to achieve the escape from suffering, which is another way of expressing Nibbana.

21
00:02:36,681 --> 00:02:41,348
So, of course, it ends with disappointment, which it has to do because the subtle aim is not true.

22
00:02:41,788 --> 00:02:47,798
You know, we're sort of chasing a false idea, fake, fake idea.

23
00:02:49,259 --> 00:02:50,562
And of course, it's exhausting.

24
00:02:50,842 --> 00:02:53,967
Yeah, you're making this great big effort, getting nowhere.

25
00:02:55,088 --> 00:03:01,138
So what we have to understand is that when we're practicing, the purpose is just to see these three characteristics.

26
00:03:02,400 --> 00:03:06,164
So, OK, the subtlety of the Buddhist teaching.

27
00:03:06,685 --> 00:03:24,186
The subtlety of the Buddha's teaching is to distinguish between an aim, which is a bit fuzzy for us, and the immediate objective which gets us there, which is to observe and examine exactly what's before us, what we're actually experiencing at this moment.

28
00:03:24,887 --> 00:03:27,090
And those are the three characteristics.

29
00:03:27,592 --> 00:03:31,758
So we've got an example of wrong effort from a monk called Sona.

30
00:03:32,300 --> 00:03:36,145
So he was desperately trying to get fully liberated and over-efforting.

31
00:03:36,887 --> 00:03:39,831
And he was about to leave the order when the news came to the Buddha.

32
00:03:39,852 --> 00:03:42,877
He goes to see him and talks about tuning a veena.

33
00:03:43,296 --> 00:03:50,207
So that's an instrument like a lute, too tight, doesn't work, too loose.

34
00:03:50,609 --> 00:03:51,530
You don't get the note.

35
00:03:52,752 --> 00:03:55,355
And so ultimately, you've got to get it just right.

36
00:03:56,432 --> 00:04:01,718
So that's that's to do with getting it right is to do without intention.

37
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:10,430
Once the intention is right, which is just to discover experience, the three characteristics, that's enough.

38
00:04:10,909 --> 00:04:12,352
We don't have to worry about the future.

39
00:04:15,055 --> 00:04:23,384
Anyway, you can understand from our life experience, you know, having expectations often leads to, well, disappointment.

40
00:04:24,293 --> 00:04:30,485
Now, in the actual discourses, the word for hope, asa, doesn't get good press at all.

41
00:04:30,704 --> 00:04:34,413
So it seems to be understood as a sort of subtle form of craving.

42
00:04:34,432 --> 00:04:40,884
And it's linked to failure and suffering in itself because it's never fulfilled.

43
00:04:41,454 --> 00:04:43,476
Somehow it's got to be transcended.

44
00:04:43,617 --> 00:04:48,502
So the Buddha talks about nirasa, which we translate as hopelessness.

45
00:04:49,062 --> 00:04:51,064
Well, that gets us towards despair.

46
00:04:51,124 --> 00:04:54,608
So there must be some misunderstanding here somewhere.

47
00:04:55,208 --> 00:04:58,071
Anyway, I'll give you a flavor of what it says in the discourses.

48
00:04:59,992 --> 00:05:04,456
This is one living in hope and one who has abandoned hope.

49
00:05:05,278 --> 00:05:08,661
One who is cut off, lost, and one who's at peace.

50
00:05:08,911 --> 00:05:12,677
So one who lives in hope is going to be cut off and lost.

51
00:05:13,358 --> 00:05:14,841
So that doesn't sound so good for us.

52
00:05:15,783 --> 00:05:18,045
Then it goes on, hope is suffering in the world.

53
00:05:19,187 --> 00:05:22,553
The person who lives with hope is called one who is defeated.

54
00:05:22,613 --> 00:05:32,430
When one's hope fails, one's hopes fails, disappointment arises and it is suffering.

55
00:05:32,451 --> 00:05:33,331
And then we've got a

56
00:05:33,970 --> 00:05:44,646
a verse from a nun, Mutateri, so one of the enlightened nuns of the period, translated by Norman, who's an expert in this.

57
00:05:45,447 --> 00:05:56,403
And somehow she says, that hope which some have here for children and wives and for the love of a woman, such hope does not apply to me.

58
00:05:56,423 --> 00:06:01,310
So I don't quite know how that fits her as a woman, but anyway.

59
00:06:02,557 --> 00:06:06,221
Again, she's abandoned all worldly hopes, at least.

60
00:06:07,665 --> 00:06:20,142
So you can see that in the scriptures, in the discourses, hope has a sort of shade of yearning for some outcome, slips into expectation.

61
00:06:20,461 --> 00:06:25,887
Now, in the Mahayana, it's redeemed, at least in our understanding of hope.

62
00:06:26,387 --> 00:06:37,021
But they do use a different word, pranidhana, which in the Pali, the language of our discourses, is panidhana, which means aspiration, a longing.

63
00:06:38,202 --> 00:06:46,653
So it fits into the Mahayana because of their bodhicitta ideal, which is a heart devoted to awakening through compassion.

64
00:06:47,579 --> 00:06:56,329
So the Bodhisattva vow, as I think most of you know, is a vow to redeem everyone before yourself.

65
00:06:56,468 --> 00:07:01,454
It's a universal awakening rather than a personal attainment.

66
00:07:03,396 --> 00:07:08,682
But again, that word, there is a word in Sanskrit, asha, which means hope, it's not used.

67
00:07:09,303 --> 00:07:10,644
So it's all a bit semantic.

68
00:07:10,805 --> 00:07:13,348
We have to just work out what this actually means.

69
00:07:13,468 --> 00:07:16,692
But of course, in our terms, if there's no hope,

70
00:07:16,958 --> 00:07:20,762
then the practice feels as though it's going to run into a cul-de-sac, yeah?

71
00:07:22,843 --> 00:07:28,170
Okay, so if we look at the word aspiration, that I think gets us better on the path.

72
00:07:28,569 --> 00:07:30,451
So here we have a word like chanda.

73
00:07:31,173 --> 00:07:36,619
So chanda is one of the four bases of spiritual power, which I covered in January 23.

74
00:07:36,939 --> 00:07:38,661
I'm sure you all remember it.

75
00:07:39,541 --> 00:07:46,189
Then the other three of the four bases are effort, consciousness and investigation.

76
00:07:46,860 --> 00:07:52,927
So we said that at the time that these four bases of power can be used in ordinary daily life.

77
00:07:53,608 --> 00:07:57,452
So you need obviously a desire to attain, to achieve something.

78
00:07:58,855 --> 00:08:00,716
And then you need the effort to get there.

79
00:08:01,237 --> 00:08:02,759
You need consciousness, of course.

80
00:08:03,319 --> 00:08:07,786
And then you need the ability to figure out what to do in the investigation.

81
00:08:09,648 --> 00:08:13,172
So here we have this word chanda, which means a very strong desire.

82
00:08:13,608 --> 00:08:15,649
And then we have the word samvega.

83
00:08:15,971 --> 00:08:17,612
The Buddha goes on about samvega.

84
00:08:18,033 --> 00:08:20,136
So this is a sort of religious fervor.

85
00:08:20,735 --> 00:08:23,098
It's a heartfelt desire to attain something.

86
00:08:23,800 --> 00:08:37,096
Now, in the Visuddhimagga, which is the medieval spiritual manual, he points to eight objects which induce this sort of devotion, gives us a sense of urgency about our practice.

87
00:08:37,817 --> 00:08:40,559
I don't think any of them will come as a surprise.

88
00:08:41,029 --> 00:08:45,895
Birth, aging, sickness and death, of course, contemplating those.

89
00:08:46,576 --> 00:09:01,514
Contemplating the idea that if we don't do the practice and we fall into error, we'll end up in one of the apaya realms, which is either purgatory, sometimes that's translated as hell, but it's not permanent, remember, thank heavens.

90
00:09:02,155 --> 00:09:08,943
And then there's rebirth as an animal or as a hungry ghost, always feeling empty.

91
00:09:09,379 --> 00:09:39,082
and in the realm of conflict the asura realm so and of course finally as number eight there is just being here in this world of samsara the world of onward going led by delusion but you can see that these realms are also quite obvious to us right here and now in the world so uh this this um

92
00:09:40,008 --> 00:10:05,307
desire this eagerness to become liberated you have to be careful not that it doesn't corrupt into expectation and this is where faith comes in really so we've got faith which you remember not a belief right it's a sense of trust of confidence so without that of course you don't do anything right i mean the obvious enemy here is skeptical doubt

93
00:10:06,046 --> 00:10:14,176
Which is obviously based on or usually based on some sort of fear, fear of failure, fear of being fooled and so on.

94
00:10:16,298 --> 00:10:20,985
Now, if we don't have that faith, that sort of faith, then you don't make a decision.

95
00:10:21,085 --> 00:10:22,167
You can't make a decision.

96
00:10:22,988 --> 00:10:23,729
You can't act.

97
00:10:24,549 --> 00:10:25,951
And this is true in daily life.

98
00:10:26,011 --> 00:10:27,813
It can become a bit destructive.

99
00:10:28,333 --> 00:10:35,023
If a person can't make up their mind about someone they're attracted to, a job they've applied for, well, the opportunity just slips away.

100
00:10:36,386 --> 00:10:39,929
I had a student actually for a while who couldn't decide whether to get out of bed or not.

101
00:10:41,530 --> 00:10:44,333
It can become a bit of a mental illness, I think.

102
00:10:45,995 --> 00:10:58,186
So even if we have this great confidence in the Buddha, the Dharma, the Sangha and the Eightfold Path, it doesn't mean it's unshakable until we reach first path and fruit.

103
00:10:58,926 --> 00:11:05,432
That's when we have such a clear insight into one of those three characteristics of existence that

104
00:11:05,868 --> 00:11:08,812
our faith becomes unshakable.

105
00:11:09,032 --> 00:11:10,192
We just know it's right.

106
00:11:11,674 --> 00:11:13,937
But until then, there's always a danger of losing it.

107
00:11:14,158 --> 00:11:17,361
And one of them is the bad behavior of monks.

108
00:11:19,184 --> 00:11:21,347
So everybody goes around saying it's hypocritical.

109
00:11:22,528 --> 00:11:25,873
But the other, of course, is that we have this unrealistic aim.

110
00:11:26,374 --> 00:11:27,654
That's the expectation.

111
00:11:28,416 --> 00:11:32,061
And then we sort of drop out and we try something else.

112
00:11:36,091 --> 00:11:46,201
So now for some people who achieve liberation, faith is their dominant quality.

113
00:11:47,121 --> 00:11:55,571
It doesn't mean to say they don't have to understand or experience the three characteristics of existence.

114
00:11:55,591 --> 00:11:58,573
It just means that it doesn't have to be so penetrative.

115
00:11:59,193 --> 00:12:01,996
They're driven on by a sense of devotion.

116
00:12:02,736 --> 00:12:05,081
So the Buddha qualifies that.

117
00:12:05,120 --> 00:12:22,029
He says there are two people, those who are driven by faith and those who are driven by curiosity and usually have a better intelligence in order to achieve a deeper insight.

118
00:12:23,773 --> 00:12:25,655
So we have somebody called puna.

119
00:12:26,243 --> 00:12:28,024
So he comes up in the Dhammapada.

120
00:12:28,586 --> 00:12:30,308
So Puna, he was a monk.

121
00:12:30,489 --> 00:12:37,317
He said of himself, whenever he learned a verse, a new verse from the Buddha, it kicked the one he just learned out of his head.

122
00:12:38,779 --> 00:12:40,822
So he didn't have a very good memory.

123
00:12:41,344 --> 00:12:49,455
And his brother told him, well, you know, you're just not going to understand the Dharma and you may as well leave and do something useful in lay life.

124
00:12:50,155 --> 00:12:52,639
So when the Buddha heard about this, he went to see him.

125
00:12:53,428 --> 00:13:02,663
And he knew of the devotion that this punna had towards himself and towards the practice, that he trusted him implicitly.

126
00:13:03,024 --> 00:13:06,048
So he gave him a cloth to rub.

127
00:13:06,068 --> 00:13:12,359
And while he's rubbing the cloth, he's supposed to be saying impermanence, impermanence, just watching impermanence.

128
00:13:13,561 --> 00:13:15,043
Well, he became fully liberated.

129
00:13:16,905 --> 00:13:20,432
And I don't think it works for everybody, but you can have a go.

130
00:13:22,657 --> 00:13:30,730
So that means that we don't have to have any big intellect to become liberated, right?

131
00:13:31,490 --> 00:13:40,245
It's really to do with opening up the intuitive intelligence, which is the active side of awareness.

132
00:13:40,346 --> 00:13:43,269
Remember that sati is satipanya.

133
00:13:43,530 --> 00:13:47,297
It's a passive awareness, observing awareness.

134
00:13:47,648 --> 00:14:11,513
uh feeling letting the information come and then that moment of grasping that's the intelligence working then intuitive a grasping intelligence so um what of hope as such you know and where does this aspiration sort of come from so

135
00:14:11,981 --> 00:14:18,750
We have to understand that there's always going to be a subtle desire of trying to attain something for me.

136
00:14:18,789 --> 00:14:24,017
And that's, of course, this tanha, which translates as thirst.

137
00:14:24,597 --> 00:14:25,979
It's a different type of tanha.

138
00:14:26,679 --> 00:14:29,442
Secondly, we see the impermanence.

139
00:14:30,104 --> 00:14:40,437
While we're meditating, while we're actually practicing, we can see the role of this tanha, this desire, and how that's a direct agent

140
00:14:40,804 --> 00:15:00,871
of creating suffering for ourselves while we're practicing we see impermanence we can see things that are insubstantial they're just arising and passing away there's nothing that remains and so every so often by being in that position we come across a sort of hint as to what nibbana is

141
00:15:02,961 --> 00:15:06,668
And here's where our real hope is grounded.

142
00:15:06,807 --> 00:15:08,610
So it's not in some future attainment.

143
00:15:09,172 --> 00:15:13,658
It's grounded in the fact that we can see these three characteristics more and more clearly.

144
00:15:14,318 --> 00:15:18,966
And then there comes that patience, you know, to await for the great day of awakening.

145
00:15:21,630 --> 00:15:31,044
Just as two asides, you know, because we're embedded in society and the way we live, the way we interact, the way we work, it affects others.

146
00:15:31,413 --> 00:15:45,171
So even on a day when we feel depressed, when things aren't going our way, there's the ability to rest somewhere within ourselves in the assurance of the Dharma that gives us an air of this acceptance.

147
00:15:45,231 --> 00:15:46,153
This is the way it is.

148
00:15:46,192 --> 00:15:49,236
And calmness, you know, this too will pass.

149
00:15:50,438 --> 00:15:57,508
And so as we're heading along the path, there comes more and more acceptance, more and more contentment.

150
00:15:57,528 --> 00:15:58,990
Yeah, that's how it works.

151
00:16:00,184 --> 00:16:09,220
It's also of great value when we come to die, believing, you know, to believe on our deathbed that we're dying into some sort of annihilation.

152
00:16:09,801 --> 00:16:11,823
It's not a particularly comforting thought.

153
00:16:13,005 --> 00:16:19,176
A poor return for a life that's generally done the best it can for the better of ourselves and others.

154
00:16:20,037 --> 00:16:25,666
So some say they are accepting this as humanist, but that's, of course, before the dying process.

155
00:16:25,907 --> 00:16:26,006
Yeah.

156
00:16:26,559 --> 00:16:30,465
I struggled myself with this sort of contemplation in my 20s.

157
00:16:30,785 --> 00:16:33,308
But of course, at that time, you never believe you're going to die.

158
00:16:33,909 --> 00:16:35,731
So that's the presumption of youth.

159
00:16:37,134 --> 00:16:46,866
Even so, it did lead me to an understanding or to an experience that proved to me personally that death wasn't an end and that it was, in fact, another beginning.

160
00:16:48,609 --> 00:16:53,495
So similarly, when somebody is dying, you know, it makes it easier for us to

161
00:16:53,880 --> 00:17:04,133
know that there is a purpose to life and that we don't have to rely on an outer power or a miracle to stop the process, but more accepting of it.

162
00:17:05,054 --> 00:17:17,607
So we have the example of the Buddha, of course, in his death, that we call the parinibbana, total nibbana, which gives us an example of someone who reaches the goal just ready to let go of life.

163
00:17:18,388 --> 00:17:20,731
Even as he's dying, he's asking people around him,

164
00:17:20,981 --> 00:17:23,144
if they've got any last questions.

165
00:17:23,585 --> 00:17:28,471
And then he says, don't be shy in asking and then regret that you didn't take this opportunity to do so.

166
00:17:31,994 --> 00:17:41,626
So in the actual discourses, when you read it and you come across the word hope and it says it's an absolute waste of time, it's a terrible thing to have.

167
00:17:42,708 --> 00:17:46,112
I think it's better to translate it as expectation, right?

168
00:17:46,480 --> 00:17:53,468
And that there is an aspiration, a real sort of grounded hope through the practice.

169
00:17:53,768 --> 00:17:55,589
That's where the hope is grounded.

170
00:17:55,990 --> 00:18:05,040
That we can see clearly that this desire is the direct cause of attachment, which creates suffering, etc.

171
00:18:05,760 --> 00:18:08,183
And that we can actually get rid of it.

172
00:18:08,605 --> 00:18:13,450
We just don't empower it and it just disappears.

173
00:18:14,509 --> 00:18:35,826
and it's doing that until we finally get down to the core desire which arises out of that sense of self the core desire of wanting to become wanting to become a person that's your core that's the core desire that we're really working with so it energizes our practice if we do it that way and uh

174
00:18:36,598 --> 00:18:40,204
You know, just have to be careful it doesn't corrupt into expectation.

175
00:18:40,665 --> 00:18:55,071
It's really putting our attention on process and abandoning any, I dare say hope, just not thinking about progress.

176
00:18:55,471 --> 00:19:00,821
So abandon progress and put your full attention upon process.

177
00:19:01,102 --> 00:19:01,542
That's it.

178
00:19:02,688 --> 00:19:14,942
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that by your practice you will find that path to liberation sooner, of course, rather than later.

